  Part 1: Linux File System Hierarchy
1. / (Root Directory)
Purpose

This is the top-level directory in Linux.
Everything in Linux starts from /.

Command
ls -l /
Example Items
bin
etc
home
var
I would use this when...

I want to understand the overall Linux file system structure.

2. /home
Purpose

Stores personal files and folders for normal users.

Command
ls -l /home
Example Items
ubuntu
user1
I would use this when...

I need to access user files, projects, or downloads.

3. /root
Purpose

Home directory of the root (admin) user.

Command
ls -l /root
Example Items
.bashrc
scripts
I would use this when...

I am logged in as root and managing system-level tasks.

4. /etc
Purpose

Contains important system configuration files.

Command
ls -l /etc
Example Items
hostname
passwd
ssh
I would use this when...

I need to change system settings or service configurations.

5. /var/log
Purpose

Stores log files generated by the system and services.

Command
ls -l /var/log
Example Items
syslog
auth.log
I would use this when...

I am troubleshooting errors or checking service activity.

6. /tmp
Purpose

Stores temporary files created by applications and users.

Command
ls -l /tmp
Example Items
tmpfile123
systemd-private
I would use this when...

I need temporary storage during testing or troubleshooting.

Additional Directories
7. /bin
Purpose

Contains essential Linux commands needed for basic system operation.

Command
ls -l /bin
Example Items
ls
cp
mv
I would use this when...

I want to use basic Linux commands.

8. /usr/bin
Purpose

Contains additional user command binaries and applications.

Command
ls -l /usr/bin
Example Items
python3
git
vim
I would use this when...

I need access to installed software and utilities.

9. /opt
Purpose

Used for optional or third-party applications.

Command
ls -l /opt
Example Items
google
custom-app
I would use this when...

I install software manually outside the default package manager
